<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,908,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species can be distinguished from its congeners by the sacculus with the ventral margin nearly straight in the male genitalia, and the ostium bursae with a spine at each side anteriorly in the female genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1184]" box="[199,1058,1015,1040]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1015,1040]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Etymology.</emphasis>
The epithet of this new species is derived from the 
<typeStatus box="[913,961,1016,1040]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,1052,1077]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Note.</emphasis>
The female of this species was not collected from the same locality as the male, and the color of its thorax and tegula as well as the color of the N-shaped pattern on the forewing are snowy white. Despite this minor difference in color, all the patterns on the forewing are the same as those in male. We herein tentatively match them as a pair.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
